AAAAAAAAwAu53W6f09irzwEAgFPzvxsAADr9DAD81x+n4gTE
     "], {{0, 960.}, {960., 0}}, {0, 255},
     ColorFunction->RGBColor],
    BoxForm`ImageTag["Byte", ColorSpace -> "RGB", Interleaving -> True],
    Selectable->False],
   DefaultBaseStyle->"ImageGraphics",
   ImageSizeRaw->{960., 960.},
   PlotRange->{{0, 960.}, {0, 960.}}]], "Input",ExpressionUUID->
  "c3089264-3d68-4bc8-ac51-ce283b5d1c6f"],
 "\nWe now have a right triangle (marked in yellow) with ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["r", "t"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "d5bf1127-99c8-41ee-8353-86f691380c00"],
 " as an unknown hypotenuse and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["\[Theta]", "t"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "d2f20ec0-8d75-472a-9984-751b9dcd0e14"],
 " as an unknown angle. However, because we have our center of mass\
\[CloseCurlyQuote] coordinates, we can determine the short and long legs \
using the x and y coordinates of the center of mass point. This means that ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["\[Theta]", "t"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "10d51ec6-ff7f-43d3-a8c3-b87ea33bf4cf"],
 " can be calculated using the inverse tangent of the x over the y, and that ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["r", "t"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "fdb67ba8-6142-45f2-8764-2e0fc87451fe"],
 " can be calculated from the Pythagorean Theorem. With the radius and angle \
solved for, we can input them into \[Tau] = F*r*sin(\[Theta]) to solve for \
the new torque on the tail. To approach this computationally, we can create a \
function to solve for the torque for any two given points of a tail."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9293546184036617`*^9, 3.9293546199188967`*^9}, {
